</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Gastric cancer is a leading cause of cancer-related deaths worldwide and is associated with an overall 5-year survival rate of less than 20%. The most common histologic subtype of gastric cancer is adenocarcinoma. Imaging techniques for evaluating gastric adenocarcinoma include endoscopic US, fluoroscopic upper gastrointestinal imaging, CT, PET/CT, and MRI. Hydrodynamic multiphasic contrast material–enhanced CT is the imaging modality of choice for preoperative clinical staging of regional, nodal, and metastatic involvement. Radiologic manifestations of gastric adenocarcinoma at double-contrast upper gastrointestinal imaging and CT include polyps, ulceration, indistensibility, wall thickening, and abnormal enhancement. There are multiple pathways of disease spread. These pathways include lymphatic dissemination; subperitoneal dissemination along the perigastric ligaments, mesentery, or omentum; direct invasion into adjacent organs; transperitoneal seeding; and hematogenous dissemination. The spread of disease is affected by the location of the tumor in the stomach, and the ligamentous and lymphatic anatomy. Key imaging features that affect clinical staging with use of the TNM classification system for gastric adenocarcinoma, as described in the eighth edition of the <i>AJCC Cancer Staging Manual,</i> are briefly discussed. Accurate radiologic assessment of gastric adenocarcinoma requires identification of perigastric ligament infiltration, regional and metastatic nodal disease, and direct and metastatic organ involvement, all of which directly affect tumor staging, treatment, and prognosis.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2019</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2019180113">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2019180113">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig1.jpeg" height="2260" width="2978" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Drawing illustrates normal gastric anatomy and vasculature.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig2a.jpeg" height="1280" width="1468" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Normal appearance of the stomach. <b>(a)</b> Double-contrast upper gastrointestinal radiograph shows the cardiac rosette (arrowhead) and normal areae gastricae (white arrow) in the gastric fundus and cardia. Note the smooth contrast material–lined contour of the stomach (black arrow), which indicates adequate mucosal coating. <b>(b)</b> EGD image shows normal areae gastricae. <b>(c, d)</b> Double-contrast upper gastrointestinal <b>(c)</b> and EGD <b>(d)</b> images show normal rugal folds (arrow), with normal distensibility seen in <b>c.</b><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig2b.jpeg" height="1280" width="1485" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Normal appearance of the stomach. <b>(a)</b> Double-contrast upper gastrointestinal radiograph shows the cardiac rosette (arrowhead) and normal areae gastricae (white arrow) in the gastric fundus and cardia. Note the smooth contrast material–lined contour of the stomach (black arrow), which indicates adequate mucosal coating. <b>(b)</b> EGD image shows normal areae gastricae. <b>(c, d)</b> Double-contrast upper gastrointestinal <b>(c)</b> and EGD <b>(d)</b> images show normal rugal folds (arrow), with normal distensibility seen in <b>c.</b><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig2c.jpeg" height="1338" width="1334" aria-labelledby="fig2c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span>. Normal appearance of the stomach. <b>(a)</b> Double-contrast upper gastrointestinal radiograph shows the cardiac rosette (arrowhead) and normal areae gastricae (white arrow) in the gastric fundus and cardia. Note the smooth contrast material–lined contour of the stomach (black arrow), which indicates adequate mucosal coating. <b>(b)</b> EGD image shows normal areae gastricae. <b>(c, d)</b> Double-contrast upper gastrointestinal <b>(c)</b> and EGD <b>(d)</b> images show normal rugal folds (arrow), with normal distensibility seen in <b>c.</b><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig2c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig2d.jpeg" height="1338" width="1617" aria-labelledby="fig2d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2d</span>. Normal appearance of the stomach. <b>(a)</b> Double-contrast upper gastrointestinal radiograph shows the cardiac rosette (arrowhead) and normal areae gastricae (white arrow) in the gastric fundus and cardia. Note the smooth contrast material–lined contour of the stomach (black arrow), which indicates adequate mucosal coating. <b>(b)</b> EGD image shows normal areae gastricae. <b>(c, d)</b> Double-contrast upper gastrointestinal <b>(c)</b> and EGD <b>(d)</b> images show normal rugal folds (arrow), with normal distensibility seen in <b>c.</b><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig2d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig3a.jpeg" height="1792" width="1596" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Normal appearance of the stomach at biphasic contrast-enhanced CT. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase CT image shows the normal layers of the greater curvature: an enhancing inner mucosal layer (black arrow), low-attenuation submucosal layer (<b>*</b>), and high-attenuation outer muscular-subserosal-serosal layer (white arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial delayed phase CT image shows a homogeneously enhancing gastric wall (arrows), with no discernible delineation of the gastric layers.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig3b.jpeg" height="1792" width="1353" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Normal appearance of the stomach at biphasic contrast-enhanced CT. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase CT image shows the normal layers of the greater curvature: an enhancing inner mucosal layer (black arrow), low-attenuation submucosal layer (<b>*</b>), and high-attenuation outer muscular-subserosal-serosal layer (white arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial delayed phase CT image shows a homogeneously enhancing gastric wall (arrows), with no discernible delineation of the gastric layers.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig4a.jpeg" height="1061" width="1571" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Anatomy of the stomach and perigastric ligaments. <b>(a)</b> Axial drawing depicts the position of the peritoneal organs and ligaments in an adult. The gastrohepatic ligament (GHL)<i>,</i> falciform ligament <i>(FL),</i> gastrosplenic ligament (GSL)<i>,</i> and splenorenal ligament (SRL) are depicted. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal drawing depicts the contiguity of the gastrocolic ligament (GCL)<i>,</i> greater omentum, and transverse mesocolon. The GHL and hepatoduodenal ligament (HDL) are continuous and form the lesser omentum and the anterior border of the lesser sac. The layers of the peritoneum comprise the visceral peritoneum <i>(VP)</i> and parietal peritoneum <i>(PP).</i> Disease can spread within the ligaments in the subperitoneal space <i>(SPS)</i> or via transperitoneal spread <i>(TPS)</i> into the peritoneal cavity.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig4b.jpeg" height="2114" width="1081" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Anatomy of the stomach and perigastric ligaments. <b>(a)</b> Axial drawing depicts the position of the peritoneal organs and ligaments in an adult. The gastrohepatic ligament (GHL)<i>,</i> falciform ligament <i>(FL),</i> gastrosplenic ligament (GSL)<i>,</i> and splenorenal ligament (SRL) are depicted. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal drawing depicts the contiguity of the gastrocolic ligament (GCL)<i>,</i> greater omentum, and transverse mesocolon. The GHL and hepatoduodenal ligament (HDL) are continuous and form the lesser omentum and the anterior border of the lesser sac. The layers of the peritoneum comprise the visceral peritoneum <i>(VP)</i> and parietal peritoneum <i>(PP).</i> Disease can spread within the ligaments in the subperitoneal space <i>(SPS)</i> or via transperitoneal spread <i>(TPS)</i> into the peritoneal cavity.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig5a.jpeg" height="1409" width="1838" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Normal perigastric ligaments at contrast-enhanced CT. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows the location of the GHL, with the left gastric artery (arrow) as an anatomic landmark, and the GSL, which contains the left gastroepiploic arteries (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows the location of the HDL, which contains the portal vein (arrow) and hepatic artery as anatomic vascular landmarks. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal CT image shows the GCL, which contains the gastroepiploic vessels (arrow), and the greater omentum <i>(GO),</i> which extends inferiorly from the transverse colon and covers the small bowel. <b>(d)</b> Axial CT image shows the SRL, which contains the distal splenic artery and proximal splenic vein (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig5b.jpeg" height="1409" width="1712" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Normal perigastric ligaments at contrast-enhanced CT. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows the location of the GHL, with the left gastric artery (arrow) as an anatomic landmark, and the GSL, which contains the left gastroepiploic arteries (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows the location of the HDL, which contains the portal vein (arrow) and hepatic artery as anatomic vascular landmarks. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal CT image shows the GCL, which contains the gastroepiploic vessels (arrow), and the greater omentum <i>(GO),</i> which extends inferiorly from the transverse colon and covers the small bowel. <b>(d)</b> Axial CT image shows the SRL, which contains the distal splenic artery and proximal splenic vein (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig5c.jpeg" height="2322" width="1599" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span>. Normal perigastric ligaments at contrast-enhanced CT. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows the location of the GHL, with the left gastric artery (arrow) as an anatomic landmark, and the GSL, which contains the left gastroepiploic arteries (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows the location of the HDL, which contains the portal vein (arrow) and hepatic artery as anatomic vascular landmarks. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal CT image shows the GCL, which contains the gastroepiploic vessels (arrow), and the greater omentum <i>(GO),</i> which extends inferiorly from the transverse colon and covers the small bowel. <b>(d)</b> Axial CT image shows the SRL, which contains the distal splenic artery and proximal splenic vein (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig5d.jpeg" height="1170" width="1947" aria-labelledby="fig5d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5d</span>. Normal perigastric ligaments at contrast-enhanced CT. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows the location of the GHL, with the left gastric artery (arrow) as an anatomic landmark, and the GSL, which contains the left gastroepiploic arteries (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows the location of the HDL, which contains the portal vein (arrow) and hepatic artery as anatomic vascular landmarks. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal CT image shows the GCL, which contains the gastroepiploic vessels (arrow), and the greater omentum <i>(GO),</i> which extends inferiorly from the transverse colon and covers the small bowel. <b>(d)</b> Axial CT image shows the SRL, which contains the distal splenic artery and proximal splenic vein (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig5d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig6.jpeg" height="994" width="1150" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. Ventral drawing depicts the stomach and perigastric ligaments, with the liver retracted superiorly. The GHL extends from the lesser curvature of the stomach and fundus <i>(F)</i> to the inferior surface of the left hepatic lobe. The HDL extends from the antrum <i>(A),</i> is a continuation of the GHL, and contains the portal triad <i>(PT).</i> The GCL extends from the greater curvature of the stomach toward the transverse colon <i>(TC)</i> and is contiguous inferiorly with the greater omentum. The GSL extends from the fundus and greater curvature toward the spleen <i>(S).</i> The SRL extends from the GSL at the splenic hilum toward the tail of the pancreas <i>(P)</i> and anterior surface of the left kidney <i>(K).</i> Regional perigastric lymph nodes (left and right paracardial nodes, lesser and greater curvature nodes, and infrapyloric and suprapyloric nodes) are noted. Bidirectional spread of disease is possible via the perigastric ligaments (arrows). <i>C</i> = cardia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig7a.jpeg" height="1427" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Polypoid lesions in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Double-contrast upper gastrointestinal radiograph shows variable-sized polypoid lesions as radiolucent filling defects (black arrow) on the dependent wall and as a barium-coated “ring shadow” (white arrow) on the nondependent wall. <b>(b)</b> Double-contrast upper gastrointestinal radiograph obtained in a different patient shows a polypoid mass (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in the patient in <b>b</b> shows a corresponding enhancing mass (arrows) in the proximal region of the stomach. Subtle fat stranding (<b>*</b>) in the region of the GSL also is seen and may represent a desmoplastic reaction or ligamentous spread of disease.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig7b.jpeg" height="1427" width="1478" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Polypoid lesions in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Double-contrast upper gastrointestinal radiograph shows variable-sized polypoid lesions as radiolucent filling defects (black arrow) on the dependent wall and as a barium-coated “ring shadow” (white arrow) on the nondependent wall. <b>(b)</b> Double-contrast upper gastrointestinal radiograph obtained in a different patient shows a polypoid mass (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in the patient in <b>b</b> shows a corresponding enhancing mass (arrows) in the proximal region of the stomach. Subtle fat stranding (<b>*</b>) in the region of the GSL also is seen and may represent a desmoplastic reaction or ligamentous spread of disease.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig7c.jpeg" height="1426" width="1676" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span>. Polypoid lesions in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Double-contrast upper gastrointestinal radiograph shows variable-sized polypoid lesions as radiolucent filling defects (black arrow) on the dependent wall and as a barium-coated “ring shadow” (white arrow) on the nondependent wall. <b>(b)</b> Double-contrast upper gastrointestinal radiograph obtained in a different patient shows a polypoid mass (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in the patient in <b>b</b> shows a corresponding enhancing mass (arrows) in the proximal region of the stomach. Subtle fat stranding (<b>*</b>) in the region of the GSL also is seen and may represent a desmoplastic reaction or ligamentous spread of disease.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig8a.jpeg" height="1271" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Ulceration. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an ulcerating mass (arrows) along the lesser curvature. A soft-tissue infiltration along the GHL, with an associated enlarged left gastric artery lymph node (<b>*</b>), also is seen. <b>(b)</b> EGD image shows a malignant ulceration crater (arrow) within an irregular tumor mound.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig8b.jpeg" height="1277" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Ulceration. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an ulcerating mass (arrows) along the lesser curvature. A soft-tissue infiltration along the GHL, with an associated enlarged left gastric artery lymph node (<b>*</b>), also is seen. <b>(b)</b> EGD image shows a malignant ulceration crater (arrow) within an irregular tumor mound.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig9a.jpeg" height="1541" width="1350" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Indistensibility. <b>(a)</b> Upper gastrointestinal radiograph shows focal gastric indistensibility, which manifests as a rigid, focally indistensible middle to distal gastric body (arrows) with a distorted rugal pattern but no gastric obstruction (scirrhous adenocarcinoma). <b>(b)</b> Upper gastrointestinal radiograph shows linitis plastica, with a diffuse absence of gastric distensibility (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig9b.jpeg" height="1541" width="1601" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Indistensibility. <b>(a)</b> Upper gastrointestinal radiograph shows focal gastric indistensibility, which manifests as a rigid, focally indistensible middle to distal gastric body (arrows) with a distorted rugal pattern but no gastric obstruction (scirrhous adenocarcinoma). <b>(b)</b> Upper gastrointestinal radiograph shows linitis plastica, with a diffuse absence of gastric distensibility (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig10a.jpeg" height="1374" width="1343" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Gastric outlet obstruction. <b>(a)</b> Double-contrast upper gastrointestinal radiograph shows persistent narrowing of the antrum (arrows), resulting in gastric outlet obstruction. <b>(b)</b> Corresponding axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows circumferential thickening (arrowheads) of the gastric antrum, with gastric outlet obstruction. An enlarged para-aortic lymph node (arrow) also is seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig10b.jpeg" height="1374" width="1806" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Gastric outlet obstruction. <b>(a)</b> Double-contrast upper gastrointestinal radiograph shows persistent narrowing of the antrum (arrows), resulting in gastric outlet obstruction. <b>(b)</b> Corresponding axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows circumferential thickening (arrowheads) of the gastric antrum, with gastric outlet obstruction. An enlarged para-aortic lymph node (arrow) also is seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig11.jpeg" height="1650" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. Diffuse thickening and enhancement (linitis plastica) of the stomach. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image obtained for further evaluation of abnormal upper gastrointestinal imaging findings (in <a href="#fig9b">Fig 9b</a>) shows marked diffuse thickening and enhancement (black arrows) of the stomach. Also note the soft-tissue thickening around the left gastric artery along the GHL (white arrow) and GCL (<b>*</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig12a.jpeg" height="1379" width="1833" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Pseudothickening. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of a decompressed stomach shows the thickened appearance of the gastric wall (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained at the same level the following day, with negative oral contrast material and adequate gastric distention, shows resolution of the thickening, which was attributable to underdistension.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig12b.jpeg" height="1379" width="1916" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Pseudothickening. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of a decompressed stomach shows the thickened appearance of the gastric wall (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained at the same level the following day, with negative oral contrast material and adequate gastric distention, shows resolution of the thickening, which was attributable to underdistension.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig13.jpeg" height="1328" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. Abnormal enhancement. Coronal contrast-enhanced parenchymal phase CT image shows focal thickening and hyperenhancement (white arrows) of the greater curvature, which differs from the enhancement of the normal gastric wall in the distal body (arrowhead). Ascites (<b>*</b>) and peritoneal nodularity (black arrow) also are present.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig14.jpeg" height="1240" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span>. Abnormal enhancement. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows circumferential wall thickening of the gastric antrum (arrow), with obliteration of the normal gastric layers but a smooth outer border (arrowhead), compatible with a T2 tumor. Given the degree of hypoattenuation, these findings are suggestive of mucinous adenocarcinoma, which was confirmed at pathologic specimen analysis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig15.jpeg" height="1846" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. T2 tumor. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows eccentric enhancement and thickening, with loss of the hypoattenuating submucosal stripe (arrowhead) along the lesser curvature. Lesser curvature adenopathy is present. Note the normal layers of the greater curvature: the enhancing inner mucosal layer (black arrow), low-attenuation submucosal layer (<b>*</b>), and high-attenuation outer muscular-subserosal-serosal layer (white arrow). <i>LN</i> = lymph node.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig16.jpeg" height="1470" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span>. T4a tumor. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows marked circumferential thickening and hyperenhancement of the gastric antrum (arrowhead), with ulceration <i>(U)</i> and evidence of gastric outlet obstruction. These findings are consistent with the patient’s history of abdominal pain and vomiting. The infiltration of the peritoneal fat (arrow) is consistent with T4a tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig17a.jpeg" height="1280" width="1705" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span>. Benign mimics of gastric malignancy. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows localized wall thickening along the greater curvature (arrows), as compared with the normal gastric wall (<b>*</b>). Pathologic analysis results confirmed a diagnosis of moderate to severe chronic gastritis and <i>H pylori</i> infection. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a different patient shows enlarged hyperattenuating rugae projecting into the gastric lumen, consistent with Ménétrier disease.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig17b.jpeg" height="1270" width="1845" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span>. Benign mimics of gastric malignancy. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows localized wall thickening along the greater curvature (arrows), as compared with the normal gastric wall (<b>*</b>). Pathologic analysis results confirmed a diagnosis of moderate to severe chronic gastritis and <i>H pylori</i> infection. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a different patient shows enlarged hyperattenuating rugae projecting into the gastric lumen, consistent with Ménétrier disease.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig18a.jpeg" height="1379" width="1875" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span>. Regional nodal stations in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse wall thickening of the proximal two-thirds of the stomach and enlarged greater curvature lymph nodes (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a different patient shows diffuse wall thickening and enhancement of the upper two-thirds of the stomach (white arrowhead), as well as enlarged hepatoduodenal (black arrow), celiac axis (black arrowhead), and infrapyloric (white arrow) regional nodal stations. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a third patient shows irregular thickening and enhancement of the lower third of the stomach (white arrowhead). There is also common hepatic artery (white arrow), splenic hilar (black arrow), and splenic artery (black arrowheads) adenopathy. Right portal vein thrombosis (black <b>*</b>) and liver metastasis (white <b>*</b>) also are noted.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig18b.jpeg" height="1384" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span>. Regional nodal stations in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse wall thickening of the proximal two-thirds of the stomach and enlarged greater curvature lymph nodes (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a different patient shows diffuse wall thickening and enhancement of the upper two-thirds of the stomach (white arrowhead), as well as enlarged hepatoduodenal (black arrow), celiac axis (black arrowhead), and infrapyloric (white arrow) regional nodal stations. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a third patient shows irregular thickening and enhancement of the lower third of the stomach (white arrowhead). There is also common hepatic artery (white arrow), splenic hilar (black arrow), and splenic artery (black arrowheads) adenopathy. Right portal vein thrombosis (black <b>*</b>) and liver metastasis (white <b>*</b>) also are noted.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig18c.jpeg" height="1379" width="1874" aria-labelledby="fig18c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18c</span>. Regional nodal stations in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse wall thickening of the proximal two-thirds of the stomach and enlarged greater curvature lymph nodes (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a different patient shows diffuse wall thickening and enhancement of the upper two-thirds of the stomach (white arrowhead), as well as enlarged hepatoduodenal (black arrow), celiac axis (black arrowhead), and infrapyloric (white arrow) regional nodal stations. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a third patient shows irregular thickening and enhancement of the lower third of the stomach (white arrowhead). There is also common hepatic artery (white arrow), splenic hilar (black arrow), and splenic artery (black arrowheads) adenopathy. Right portal vein thrombosis (black <b>*</b>) and liver metastasis (white <b>*</b>) also are noted.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig18c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig19.jpeg" height="1522" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig19" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19</span>. Distant nodal stations. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows para-aortic (arrows) and middle colic (arrowhead) adenopathy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig19">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig20a.jpeg" height="1313" width="1861" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span>. T3 tumor. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows gastric wall thickening <i>(T)</i>, with soft-tissue infiltration along the GCL (arrow), which contains the gastroepiploic vessels (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in the same patient shows the tumor (<b>*</b>), evidence of gastric outlet obstruction, hepatic metastasis <i>(M),</i> and soft-tissue thickening along the GHL (arrowhead), which contains the left gastric artery. There is also soft-tissue thickening along the HDL (white arrow), which is delineated by the portal triad, and extension into the GSL (black arrow), which contains the short gastric arteries.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig20b.jpeg" height="1313" width="1659" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span>. T3 tumor. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows gastric wall thickening <i>(T)</i>, with soft-tissue infiltration along the GCL (arrow), which contains the gastroepiploic vessels (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in the same patient shows the tumor (<b>*</b>), evidence of gastric outlet obstruction, hepatic metastasis <i>(M),</i> and soft-tissue thickening along the GHL (arrowhead), which contains the left gastric artery. There is also soft-tissue thickening along the HDL (white arrow), which is delineated by the portal triad, and extension into the GSL (black arrow), which contains the short gastric arteries.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig21a.jpeg" height="1330" width="1857" aria-labelledby="fig21a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span>. T4b tumor in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse nodular thickening of the stomach wall, with direct invasion and fistulization (arrows) between the gastric body and a thickened colonic splenic flexure (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a different patient shows focal mural thickening of the gastric fundus (white arrowhead) with soft-tissue infiltration along the celiac axis (arrow) and retroperitoneum, as well as direct invasion of the left adrenal gland (black arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig21a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig21b.jpeg" height="1330" width="1694" aria-labelledby="fig21b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span>. T4b tumor in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse nodular thickening of the stomach wall, with direct invasion and fistulization (arrows) between the gastric body and a thickened colonic splenic flexure (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a different patient shows focal mural thickening of the gastric fundus (white arrowhead) with soft-tissue infiltration along the celiac axis (arrow) and retroperitoneum, as well as direct invasion of the left adrenal gland (black arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig21b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig22.jpeg" height="1402" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig22" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22</span>. Metastatic disease. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows omental nodules (arrowheads) with ascites (<b>*</b>) in a patient with gastric adenocarcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig22">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig23a.jpeg" height="1982" width="1576" aria-labelledby="fig23a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23a</span>. Large Krukenberg tumors in the setting of subtle gastric cancer. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows ascites and a large pelvic mass (<b>*</b>). Given the large burden of pelvic disease, these findings were believed to represent primary ovarian cancer with metastatic disease. However, findings in frozen specimens obtained at oophorectomy and exploratory laparoscopy confirmed the diagnosis of bilateral Krukenberg tumors, with gastric adenocarcinoma as the primary malignancy. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows, in retrospect, a small focal area of gastric thickening (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig23a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180113/asset/images/large/rg.2019180113.fig23b.jpeg" height="1365" width="1775" aria-labelledby="fig23b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23b</span>. Large Krukenberg tumors in the setting of subtle gastric cancer. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows ascites and a large pelvic mass (<b>*</b>). Given the large burden of pelvic disease, these findings were believed to represent primary ovarian cancer with metastatic disease. However, findings in frozen specimens obtained at oophorectomy and exploratory laparoscopy confirmed the diagnosis of bilateral Krukenberg tumors, with gastric adenocarcinoma as the primary malignancy. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows, in retrospect, a small focal area of gastric thickening (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180113&amp;id=fig23b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Ferlay J, Soerjomataram I, Dikshit R, et al. Cancer incidence and mortality worldwide: sources, methods and major patterns in GLOBOCAN 2012. <em>Int J Cancer</em> 2015;136(5):E359–E386.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1002/ijc.29210">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25220842/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Cancer+incidence+and+mortality+worldwide%3A+sources%2C+methods+and+major+patterns+in+GLOBOCAN+2012&amp;author=J+Ferlay&amp;author=I+Soerjomataram&amp;author=R+Dikshit&amp;publication_year=2015&amp;journal=Int+J+Cancer&amp;pages=E359-E386&amp;doi=10.1002%2Fijc.29210&amp;pmid=25220842">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Yang D, Hendifar A, Lenz C, et al. Survival of metastatic gastric cancer: significance of age, sex and race/ethnicity. <em>J Gastrointest Oncol</em> 2011;2(2):77–84.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22811834/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Survival+of+metastatic+gastric+cancer%3A+significance+of+age%2C+sex+and+race%2Fethnicity&amp;author=D+Yang&amp;author=A+Hendifar&amp;author=C+Lenz&amp;publication_year=2011&amp;journal=J+Gastrointest+Oncol&amp;pages=77-84&amp;pmid=22811834">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="r3" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Horton KM, Fishman EK. Current role of CT in imaging of the stomach. <em>RadioGraphics</em> 2003;23(1):75–87.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.231025071">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12533643/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Current+role+of+CT+